<TEXT>
senators came to bury bullfrog county 
not to praise it they voted to remove from the books the desert 
jurisdiction where no one lives and where the federal government 
wants to dump nuclear waste 
not that i loved bullfrog less but that i loved nevada 
more state sen thomas hickey said tuesday in a parody of 
shakespeares speech that marc antony delivered after julius caesar 
was slain by his closest confidant 
hickey was a key senate sponsor of the 1987 bill that created 
the 144squaremile county with no roads and a government seat in 
carson city 270 miles to the north residents included snakes 
lizards coyotes and kangaroos rats but no humans 
bullfrog county was formed to encompass yucca mountain the only 
area in the nation the federal department of energy is studying as 
the possible site for a highlevel nuclear waste repository 
the intent was to collect millions of dollars from the federal 
government through a property tax rate of 5 per 100 of assessed 
valuation the highest allowed under the nevada constitution 
a retired state supreme court justice ruled last year that 
bullfrog county was unconstitutional on more than two dozen 
grounds including the lack of a representative government because 
no people lived at the desert site 
although hickey mourned the countys death starting his eulogy 
with oh mighty bullfrog senate majority leader bill raggio 
led a group who said the county should stay on nevadas law books 
as a civics lesson 
raggio warned in the waning hours of the 1987 session that 
bullfrog county would falter in the courts he said tuesday that 
historians should be reminded of the states attempt to create 
special legislation to squeeze money out of the federal government 
and into state coffers 
i dont think we should let this go without learning a 
lesson raggio said 
raggio was one of the dissenters in tuesdays 155 vote that 
sent the measure to erase the bullfrog proposal from the books to 
the assembly for further consideration 
hickey said a bill would likely be introduced in the senate to 
establish a special emergency district around yucca mountain so 
local governments could collect grants instead of taxes for the 
proposed dump project as allowed by federal law 
nye county from which bullfrog was carved filed the lawsuit 
that sought to have bullfrog county declared unconstitutional 
under current plans the dump would house waste from nuclear 
reactors for 10000 years and would open early in the next century 
if the energy department determines yucca mountain is stable enough 
gov bob miller and most other state officials strongly oppose 
locating the dump in the state saying yucca mountain has a history 
of volcanic and seismic activity 
</TEXT>
