<TEXT>
the agriculture departments decision to hold 
public hearings this summer on a plan to reduce the number of 
federal inspectors at plants that turn out chicken soup hot dogs 
and other meat and poultry products has qualified approval from 
both industry and consumer groups 
the proposal was announced last november to carry out a 1986 law 
that would be tougher on inspections of the most troublesome 
processing plants but ease up on those with good records 
one of the goals is to take advantage of computers and other 
technology that could replace daybyday surveillance by federal 
inspectors 
periodic reviews would be held at the plants with good records 
and these operations would be expected to maintain a high level of 
selfpolicing in order to retain usda approval 
lester m crawford administrator of the departments food 
safety and inspection service said tuesday the agency will 
postpone final decisions on some of the most controversial parts of 
its improved processing inspection plan until after the 
hearings 
but crawford said a final decision on certain criteria or 
standards for implementing the riskbased system will be made 
in the near future 
there are more than 7000 meat and poultry plants in the united 
states including about 6300 that turn out products such as hot 
dogs beef stew chicken soup luncheon meats and scores of other 
items only the processing plants would be covered by the 
streamlined inspection system it would not apply to slaughter 
plants which would remain under continuous federal inspection 
officials have estimated that the number of usda inspectors at 
the processing plants would be reduced by half by retirements and 
resignations the program would rely increasingly on good 
plants policing themselves 
crawford said his agency fsis will maintain the inspection 
work force at its current strength for the time being 
manly molpus president of the industrysupported american meat 
institute said the decision was a step in the right direction 
but that his organization and fsis are still far apart in our 
views of how improved processing inspection should be implemented 
molpus said the announcement did not provide a clear fix on 
how the agency should proceed and that we assume everything is on 
the table for discussion over the next several months 
rep ted weiss dny chairman of a house subcommittee on 
human resources and intergovernmental relations said that a 
subcommittee hearing on the streamlined inspection program will 
proceed as scheduled tuesday 
weiss in a statement said the usdas announcement recognized 
that this proposal is seriously flawed and that the department 
cannot justify reducing the frequency of inspections at this 
time 
tom devine legal director for the government accountability 
project which was joined by the consumer nutrition institute in 
opposing the usda proposal called the departments announcement 
a tentative victory for common sense 
devine in a telephone interview added it means we can begin 
the real public debate on how to change the inspection program 
without a fait accompli once they cut the numbers of inspectors in 
half most of the options are gone except an honor system 
devine said the usda announcement also raises the stakes for 
the weiss hearing next week 
it means we dont have to wait for fsis to schedule hearings 
this summer to begin the public debate he said 
