<TEXT>
the state is suing the us labor department and 
its job corps program charging the federal agency with illegally 
requiring aids tests for applicants 
in a complaint filed tuesday in us district court state 
attorney general james shannon accused the agency of violating 
federal law by requiring job corps applicants to be tested for aids 
antibodies and using positive test results to keep young people out 
of a residential job corps program 
shannon was joined in the lawsuit by a woman identified as 
jane doe who was described as a massachusetts resident who was 
removed from a job corps program on the basis of a positive aids 
antibody test she is represented by the disability law center and 
by the gay and lesbian advocates and defenders 
the federal government did not reply immediately in court to 
shannons complaint paul williams a spokesman for the labor 
department in washington said the agency would not comment on 
pending litigation 
the complaint alleges at least six massachusetts residents have 
been excluded from job corps residential programs the state 
charges that the job corps policy discriminates against people who 
have or are perceived as having a disability in violation of 
federal laws protecting the handicapped from discrimination 
shannon also charged that the policy violates the administrative 
procedure act because it was adopted without public notice or 
hearings and that it violates privacy rights 
this policy has a devastating impact on the lives of many 
youths who are trying to better themselves it is tragic that the 
job corps is abandoning the young people it is intended to help 
shannon said 
the job corps a nationwide program within the labor department 
provides education and training to youths between ages 16 and 24 
who need special assistance in preparing for work because of 
disruptive home lives or cultural deprivation 
about 700 young men and women are enrolled in the two 
residential job corps programs in massachusetts in north grafton 
and in chicopee 
according to the complaint jane doe is a 20yearold high 
school dropout who replied to a job corps tv advertisement last 
august she applied to the grafton center for training in 
wordprocessing and was accepted 
on aug 30 doe enrolled in the program the next day she 
underwent a medical exam that included a test for exposure to aids 
without any advance counseling about the test or its significance 
on sept 12 she was summoned from class and told that she had 
tested positive shannon said she was immediately dismissed from 
the program with virtually no meaningful counseling or 
support he said 
aides to shannon said the job corps made minor changes in its 
aids testing policy after a similar lawsuit was filed last year in 
federal court in washington dc 
shortly after the bush administration took office in january 
shannon said job corps officials used an internal memorandum to 
revise the policy still requiring testing but evaluating results 
on a casebycase basis 
