of the government in 1987 had banned british newspapers from 
publishing excerpts from the book but no longer are enforced 
if found to have been in contempt of court the newspapers can 
be fined or at worst their editors jailed the extent of the 
fine or jail term is at the discretion of the judge 
prime minister margaret thatchers government has failed to 
suppress the book in three years of court fights in london 
australia hong kong and elsewhere 
the government unsuccessfully argued that wright once a senior 
officer with britains counterespionage agency mi5 violated a 
pledge by british intelligence officers never to reveal details of 
their secret work 
spycatcher published in 40 countries including the united 
states became a best seller despite government attempts to quash 
its publication 
british authorities made no attempt to stop the book being 
brought into britain but temporary injunctions banned british news 
media from publishing extracts readily available in newspapers 
abroad 
after several court hearings the law lords britains highest 
court last october rejected the governments request to make the 
interim injunctions permanent 
the law lords charged wright with violating his secrecy oath but 
lifted the temporary injunctions saying any damage to british 
security already had been caused by the books publication abroad 
nevertheless spycatcher effectively has been banned in britain 
as publishers will not publish it for fear of being prosecuted 
under the official secrets act 
in a statement tuesday the independent editor andreas whittam 
smith said he decided it was in the public interest to publish 
wrights allegations of treason in mi5 
spycatcher alleges the late mi5 chief sir roger hollis was a 
soviet agent a claim the government says never was substantiated 
the book also claims mi5 officers eavesdropped on foreign 
embassies bungled operations stole documents plotted to 
assassinate egyptian president gamal abdel nasser and plotted to 
destabilize harold wilsons labor party government 
</TEXT>
