<TEXT>
attorneys are seeking the release of a 
man whom state officials now agree didnt get a fair trial when he 
was convicted in the poisoning deaths of his seven children 
james j richardson 53 was sentenced to die in the electric 
chair after his 1968 trial his sentence was commuted to life in 
prison after the us supreme court struck down the death penalty 
in 1972 
last fall newspaper reports claimed that prosecutors withheld 
evidence from defense attorneys richardsons advocates say 
prosecutors framed him and suggest desoto county officials 
protected a more likely suspect the childrens babysitter 
after months of investigation this year a special prosecutor 
appointed by gov bob martinez confirmed evidence was withheld and 
attorney general bob butterworth concluded richardson received an 
unfair trial 
chief justice raymond ehrlich of the florida supreme court said 
he intends to appoint a special judge to reconsider richardsons 
conviction 
in the meantime richardsons attorney ellis rubin said 
tuesday that he has asked that richardson be released from prison 
and he predicted richardson could be out this week 
a clemency hearing had been scheduled for thursday but the 
governor postponed it after his special prosecutor concluded 
evidence was withheld 
he butterworth thinks theres an injustice hes going to 
want to see that guy out yesterday said jim york the attorney 
generals chief deputy the constitution doesnt require that 
every trial be perfect but it sure requires that it be fair 
richardson is serving his sentence at the tomoka correctional 
institution near daytona beach he is eligible for parole in 1993 
once an illiterate and indigent migrant worker richardson 
educated himself while behind bars and earned the respect of 
corrections officials by compiling an immaculate disciplinary 
record 
he was convicted of only one count of firstdegree murder for 
the death of his eldest child 8yearold stepdaughter betty jean 
bryant she and her six siblings the youngest 2 years old died 
oct 2526 1967 
on oct 25 they had eaten a lunch of rice beans hogshead 
cheese and grits that was laced with the pesticide parathion 
the food had been prepared ahead of time and served at noontime 
by their neighbor betsy reese while richardson and his wife 
annie mae richardson were miles away picking oranges 
among questions now raised about the prosecution was the 
contention that richardson had purchased life insurance policies 
covering the children 
jurors werent told that although richardson intended to buy the 
policies he hadnt made the first premium payment and the policies 
hadnt taken effect when the children were killed 
in 1970 attorney mark lane published a book called arcadia 
in which he concluded richardson had been railroaded but nothing 
came of it the family lived in a arcadia about 35 miles east of 
sarasota 
