<DOCNO> AP890405-0100 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
key events in polands roundtable 
talks 
aug 26 1988 interior minister gen czeslaw kiszczak faced 
with a second severe wave of strikes proposes negotiations with 
the opposition which is led by the independent solidarity union 
movement that has refused to fade seven years after being banned 
under martial law 
sept 3 1988 strikes end after 19 days when solidarity leader 
lech walesa appeals for time to talk with the government 
oct 24 1988 a round pine table is set up at a government 
palace but the date for the start of the talks remains in doubt as 
both sides argue 
nov 25 1988 with prospects for talks dim the table is 
dismantled 
nov 30 1988 walesa and alfred miodowicz head of the union 
alliance created by the government to replace solidarity after 
martial law hold a live television debate and walesas convincing 
performance rekindles plans for the talks 
jan 17 1989 the communist party leadership decides 
solidarity can be legalized under certain conditions meeting 
solidaritys prerequisite for the talks 
jan 22 1989 solidarity leadership agrees to negotiate with 
the government 
feb 6 1989 the talks begin the government and opposition 
representatives form teams to handle political union and economic 
reforms and smaller committees are assigned specific issues 
feb 9 1989 as small strikes break out nationwide walesa 
asks workers to stay on the job and give the talks a chance 
feb 24 1989 negotiators agree on allowing legal independent 
unions including solidarity the farmers rural solidarity and the 
students union known as nzs 
march 9 1989 negotiators agree on election reforms that will 
create a senate the first freely elected legislative body in the 
east bloc they also agree to create the office of the presidency 
expected to be retained by the communist party and its allies 
which is guaranteed a majority in the existing sejm for the first 
election 
march 22 1989 the sejm begins considering the reforms even 
before end of the talks 
april 4 1989 kiszczak and walesa end their final meeting but 
snags remain and walesa returns to gdansk as aides struggle to 
resolve the final issues including indexing wages to price 
increases 
april 5 1989 walesa announces solidarity has its key demand 
legalization and will sign the accord kiszczak and walesa 
conclude the new social contract for polands future 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
