<TEXT>
the two aides secretary of state james a 
baker iii sent to moscow to inspect the us embassy in the soviet 
capital have recommended that part of the chancery be salvaged a 
bush administration official said wednesday 
their recommendation is to dismantle the top floors which are 
believed to be riddled with eavesdropping devices and to replace 
them with bugfree floors or an adjoining annex said the official 
who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the inspection was conducted two weeks ago by nicholas m salgo 
a former us ambassador to hungary and ivan selin who is to be 
undersecretary of state for management 
they told baker on their return that refurbishing the building 
or even constructing an annex would be cheaper than razing the 
chancery and starting over the estimated cost of tearing down and 
rebuilding is 500 million 
the official said baker would take into consideration the views 
of key members of congress rep neal smith diowa chairman of a 
house appropriations subcommittee last month opposed spending the 
500 million others on capitol hill are inclined to agree with the 
conclusion last year of a washington area engineering firm that 
starting over was the only way to make the chancery secure 
a trade group headed by dwayne o andreas chairman of archer 
daniels midland co offered to buy the building for use as 
business offices 
andreas is cochairman of the usussr trade and economic 
council which promotes trade between the two superpowers he made 
the offer on behalf of a consortium of us companies which would 
use the building as a moscow headquarters 
the soviets would have to approve any sale because the building 
was intended for use as a new embassy built under a 1972 agreement 
between the two countries 
a study done for the reagan administration by former defense 
secretary james r schlesinger recommended last year that the top 
three floors be dismantled and rebuilt while an annex also was put 
up next to the chancery 
