<DOCNO> AP890405-0114 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
people who smoke while they work typically burn up 
an extra 100 calories a day a discovery that helps explain why 
most put on weight when they give up cigarettes researchers report 
experts long have suspected that smoking boosts the bodys 
metabolism but the new research shows that this effect is 
significantly greater if people smoke while they are busy instead 
of only when resting 
the finding also helps explain while some people put on more 
weight than others when they stop smoking 
if people tend to smoke only while they are on coffee breaks 
or while relaxing at home watching tv they wont gain as much 
weight when they quit said dr kenneth a perkins those who 
smoke while active are likely to be thinner to begin with because 
of their smoking so they risk putting on more when they stop 
researchers long have wondered why people usually gain a few 
pounds when they quit cigarettes studies have shown people often 
eat more food especially sugar after quitting but there also was 
evidence that they burn fewer calories 
the new research based on measurements of the effects of 
nicotine suggests that the drugs effect on the bodys metabolism 
the rate at which it uses up calories is significantly more 
important than experts had suspected 
the research conducted by perkins and colleagues at the 
university of pittsburgh school of medicine was published in 
thursdays new england journal of medicine 
in an accompanying editorial dr nancy a rigotti of harvard 
said the team made an important contribution to understanding 
the way smoking affects metabolism 
until our cultural obsession with slenderness abates she 
wrote we must pay more attention to the way weight gain impedes 
efforts to stop smoking if we are to continue the progress of the 
past quarter century toward a smokefree society 
smokers on average weigh five to 10 pounds less than 
nonsmokers and they usually put on this much weight after they 
give up cigarettes 
studies by perkins and others suggest that smokers are thinner 
because nicotine somehow makes their bodies burn more calories 
until now this effect has been studied only when people are 
completely inactive and the impact of nicotine appeared to be 
slight raising the metabolism about 5 percent 
however perkins noted that people often smoke while working 
walking and moving about so he studied the effects of nicotine 
during light exercise to more closely mirror real life 
he found that nicotine during exercise boosted metabolism about 
12 percent he calculated that someone who smokes steadily through 
the day will burn up an extra 100 calories about twothirds of 
them while active and the remainder while resting 
the loss of 100 calories a day could add up to about 10 pounds 
of lost weight a year 
however perkins said the news is not all bad for people 
thinking about quitting because they can make up for their slower 
metabolic rates by getting some extra exercise 
all you would need to do is walk about a mile extra a day to 
counter that he said thats not as hard as it sounds 
he said people should also remember that gaining a few pounds 
after giving up cigarettes is harmless while continuing to smoke 
is a major health hazard 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

