he said the department was imposing a ban on an additional 24 
types of guns to review their suitability for sporting purposes 
among other things he said the administration wants to make 
sure that no foreign manufacturer suffered a needless weakening of 
its competitive position in the export market and so therefore the 
ban was expanded 
the president believes that by working closely with law 
enforcement groups sportsmen concerned citizen groups and 
congress we can resolve these problems fitzwater said 
treasurys bureau of alcohol tobacco and firearms announced the 
initial ban on march 14 on the import of the ak47s and certain 
similar weapons but said the action could be reversible 
it said the move was necessary to head off an imminent flood of 
the assault weapons into the united states 
bush earlier had asked federal drug coordinator william bennett 
to recommend what should be done about the increasing flow of the 
weapons calls for such a ban had been prompted by scores of 
drugrelated shootings and the recent slaying of five california 
schoolchildren 
fitzwater said the new action was not guided so much by growing 
public opinion against such weapons as by a desire to make sure 
that one company did not gain a competitive advantage over another 
through the import ban 
this is an effort to equalize that matter he said 
the spokesman conceded that todays action still would not 
affect the production and distribution of domestically made assault 
rifles 
there is some unfairness in that those weapons are still being 
produced unfortunately it is not something we can do anything 
about he said 
to do anything about domestically manufactured weapons would 
require a change in the law fitzwater said 
he said that the 90day review of the entire subject ordered by 
bush on march 15 is progressing 
