<TEXT>
overall spending by state governments will 
exceed revenues in both fiscal 1989 and 1990 while emergency 
reserves will decline next year to their lowest level since the 
recession early in the decade the national governors association 
reported wednesday 
officials noted that the shift to deficit spending comes in the 
face of a healthy economy and expressed concern that a new 
downturn coupled with recent requirements for more state spending 
on health care education and prisons would make matters worse 
for now the majority of states remain on fair to good financial 
footing with much of the current stress centered in the northeast 
despite low unemployment and robust growth in personal income in 
that region of 10 states forced to trim their original 1989 
budgets half were in the northeast new york and massachusetts 
together accounted for 815 million of the 115 billion in overall 
cuts 
the governors association said 24 states are considering tax 
increases for 1990 with about half of those looking at boosts in 
personal income and business taxes increases in cigarette taxes 
ranging from 35 cents to 18 cents per pack have been proposed in 
10 states eleven governors are seeking to raise fuel taxes nine 
states are considering alcohol tax increases 
all states except vermont are barred by their constitutions or 
laws from deficit spending but many are increasingly dipping into 
past surpluses their socalled rainyday accounts to make up 
for revenue shortfalls 
the governors semiannual fiscal survey showed that overall 
the states ended fiscal 1988 with 98 billion in reserve but that 
total will drop to 9 billion in 1989 and 81 billion in 1990 
more alarming the amount available for fiscal emergencies will 
fall to 3 percent of total budgeted spending next year as 
expenditures continue to rise well below the 5 percent benchmark 
eyed required by wall street for superior bond ratings 
the projected 1990 reserve figure would be the lowest since the 
15 percent logged in the major recession year of 1983 and 
compares with 42 percent for fiscal 1988 and 35 percent for 1989 
the governors report compiled jointly with the national 
association of state budget officers asked if total reserves 
decline when the national economy is strong what will happen with 
the national economy weakens 
raymond c scheppach executive director of the governors 
association said federal spending constraints coupled with new 
laws requiring greater state spending on catastrophic health care 
and nursing homes both components of the medicaid program are 
at the root of the squeeze he also cited needs for more state 
spending on education and new corrections costs arising from 
longer prison terms and prison overcrowding 
he said the state governments are clearly at risk if there is 
an economic slowdown 
the report said the states will spend a total of 2553 billion 
against revenues of 2534 billion in 1989 with projections for 
expenditures of 2715 billion against revenues of 2682 billion 
in 1990 by contrast the states ended fiscal 1988 with a 68 
billion surplus 
state spending increased 7 percent in 1988 went up 8 percent 
this year and will climb at a pace of 64 percent next year the 
report said when measured against inflation real state spending 
increased 29 percent in 1988 and again this year and will go up 
at a slower 13 percent pace next year 
</TEXT>
