<TEXT>
a twin attack by minnesotas twin cities 
on plastic food packaging advanced wednesday with st paul 
embracing a tough prohibition that the industry is considered 
likely to challenge in court 
the city councils public works committee voted unanimously to 
approve an ordinance identical to one enacted friday across the 
mississippi river in minneapolis since the committee is made up of 
all seven council members its vote left little doubt how the 
council will vote on the issue on april 27 
the real theme behind all of this is to send a message to the 
industry that we can no longer continue to produce nonrecyclable 
food packaging said councilman bob long who wrote the ordinance 
and shared it with minneapolis we cannot afford it 
environmentally and we cannot afford it economically 
advocates say plastics take up too much space and do not 
decompose in landfills and cant safely be incinerated either 
but a plastics industry group whose 11 company members have 
committed 1 million a year toward addressing those concerns says 
the twin cities ordinances are unnecessary 
its not like we need to receive a message said roger 
bernstein whose washingtonbased council for solid waste solutions 
was formed in october 1988 
i think the twin cities are looking at more of a quick fix 
that gives them the appearance of having done something rather than 
working with the industry for a solution 
in testimony before the council dave locey of the minnesota 
soft drink association said you are giving no guidance to these 
people who manufacture the packaging as to what is environmentally 
safe 
he also argued that the ordinance is discriminatory in singling 
out plastic food packaging to regulate 
philip byrne an assistant city attorney responded that 
legislation doesnt have to address all aspects of a problem to be 
constitutional 
i have been assuming right from day one that there will be 
litigation on this ordinance he said 
the ordinances would prohibit grocery stores and restaurants 
primarily fastfood outlets from selling food wrapped in plastics 
that cant be recycled arent biodegradable or arent returnable 
among the items banned would be foam egg cartons and trays in 
meat packages plastic products shipped into the state such as 
ketchup bottles and peanut butter jars grocery bags drinking 
cups serving trays and plates 
the ordinances which would take effect july 1 1990 expand on 
less stringent laws adopted in new yorks suffolk county berkeley 
calif and portland ore long said 
suffolk county and berkeley dont include plastics shipped in 
portland only bans plastic foam he said 
in the twin cities exceptions would be made for packages that 
have no substitute such as microwave dinner trays and for plastic 
soda bottles and milk jugs provided the cities include them in 
curbside recycling programs 
the cities health commissioners would be empowered to make 
other exceptions for example if acceptable packaging would put a 
company at a clear economic disadvantage 
industry officials said they were trying to determine which 
products would be affected 
were still taking stock literally said joel hoiland 
president of the minnesota grocers association 
i would call it an administrative nightmare said raymond 
peterson of the amoco foam products co in chippewa falls wis 
the grocers group is turning its attention to a recycling bill 
pending in the state senate that would preempt local ordinances 
hoiland said 
john ruston of the nonprofit environmental defense fund in new 
york said that the local ordinances are a largely symbolic way of 
addressing a national environmental problem 
still he said i think it will cause some plastic packaging 
companies to realize they can hold a marketing advantage if there 
are products packaged in environmentally beneficial containers 
</TEXT>
