<TEXT>
the un food and agriculture organization says 15 
developing countries require exceptional or emergency 
assistance to make up for serious food shortages 
in a confidential report obtained by the associated press 
wednesday the romebased agency listed the countries as angola 
bangladesh ethiopia haiti jamaica laos lebanon mozambique 
nicaragua peru sierra leone somalia sri lanka sudan and 
vietnam 
it said these nations suffered an exceptional shortfall in 
food supplies due to crop failures natural disasters interruption 
of imports disruption of distribution or other factors 
the report also listed 11 countries with unfavorable crop 
prospects this year algeria angola argentina lesotho morocco 
mozambique nicaragua peru sri lanka tunisia and zimbabwe 
fao directorgeneral edouard saouma said poor countries will be 
hard hit this year by an overall increase of more than 5 billion 
in the purchase price of food imports the figure is projected to 
reach 176 billion up from 123 billion last year 
the increases will further worsen the balance of payments 
position of many of the lowincome food deficit countries saouma 
said in a speech monday to the faos committee on world food 
security which is meeting this week in rome 
he said many developing countries will also be hurt by a 
significant decrease in food aid shipments partly due to 
inadequate contributions to the international emergency food 
reserve shipments this year are estimated at 97 million tons 
about onefourth less than last year he said 
saouma said world production of staple foods fell below 
consumption in 1988 for the second straight year mainly due to 
drought in the united states and canada 
as a result world grain stocks have dropped to 16 percent of 
annual consumption requirements the lowest ratio since the world 
food crisis of the early 1970s 
fao had estimated that grain output in 1989 would need to 
increase by 200 million tons or 12 percent to rebuild stocks to 
the minimum level required for world food security but saouma 
said it now seems certain this outcome will not be achieved 
even if weather is favorable for the remainder of the season 
he said any adverse crop conditions in major producing regions 
would have disastrously adverse effects 
</TEXT>
