<TEXT>
immigration officials refused wednesday 
to free from prison a dutch visitor who says he has aids saying 
that allowing him to attend a forum on the disease might endanger 
the health of others 
parole is an extreme item that would be used only in extreme 
circumstances said tom schiltgen district director of the 
immigration and naturalization service explaining his rejection of 
the request from hans paul verhoef 
however schiltgen said a decision is likely thursday on 
verhoefs request for a waiver from immigration laws denying united 
states entry to individuals with dangerous contagious disease 
schiltgen said that to grant a waiver the ins must verify that 
verhoefs disease does not pose a health threat and that the us 
government would not incur expenses for verhoefs care 
verhoef wants to attend a conference on aids in san francisco 
verhoef was taken into custody at minneapolisst paul 
international airport sunday by customs officials who discovered 
the aids drug azt in his baggage and then questioned him about the 
disease verhoef 31 of rotterdam an aids prevention worker in 
his country told immigration officials he has acquired immune 
deficiency syndrome and was en route to the aids conference 
you cant get aids from seeing me or giving me a hand or 
something verhoef said you have to do other things which im 
not intending to do so i dont think theres any danger of me 
spreading the disease 
his detention prompted denunciations from aids activists but 
immigration officials said they were just following the law 
we are holding mr verhoef as an excludable alien because he 
has a dangerous and contagious disease schiltgen said 
schiltgen said tests would be conducted to verify verhoef has 
the disease before authorities proceed with the case the tests 
should be completed within a few days he said 
for years immigration laws have required people who want to 
enter the united states to establish they have no dangerous 
contagious diseases congress added aids to that list of diseases 
in 1987 
verhoefs incarceration provoked protests at the state capitol 
in st paul and criticism of the inss handling of the case from 
sister mary madonna ashton the state health commissioner 
there was no need to treat mr verhoef in this fashion while 
the legal issues surrounding his case were resolved said ashton 
having this disease is not a crime and treating it has though it 
were can serve no useful purpose 
