<TEXT>
in the first prosecution under a 1986 
antiapartheid law an aviation company and its chairman pleaded 
guilty wednesday to importing four jet engines that were owned by 
south african airways 
air ground equipment sales inc of west babylon ny and its 
chairman robert fessler had been indicted monday 
their guilty pleas were part of an agreement with federal 
prosecutors who said the case was the first prosecution under the 
comprehensive antiapartheid act of 1986 
fessler told us district judge mark a costantino of brooklyn 
that he had been negotiating to buy the engines from south african 
airways before the law was enacted the company went ahead with the 
purchase and shipped the engines to israel where a deal to sell 
them to an israeli company fell through he said 
a business judgment was made to continue the deal after the 
law was enacted fessler said the engines were shipped to the 
united states in august 1987 
i realized at the time we were dealing with a subsidiary of 
the south african government he said after he pleaded guilty to 
the charge 
the 1986 law bans the importation of goods grown produced 
manufactured by marketed or otherwise imported by organizations 
that are part of or controlled by the south african government 
congress enacted the sanction in an effort to pressure south 
africas whiteminority government to modify its system of racial 
separation 
as part of the plea agreement three other counts in the 
indictment against fessler are to be dismissed at sentencing june 
9 fessler faces up to 10 years in prison and a 250000 fine 
the company entered its plea through an attorney jerry markham 
it pleaded guilty to the antiapartheid law and customs fraud for 
using falsified documents 
air ground agreed to pay a 1 million fine and forfeit the 
engines to the us government the engines which are used in 
boeing 747 jumbo jets are valued at 1 million apiece 
the company buys sells and leases airplane equipment 
