correlated with greater religiousness 
the researchers urge more evenhanded studies in this area 
citing evidence of the importance of religion to most people and 
pointing out that psychiatry generally has not considered the 
religious factor 
that aspect has been largely ignored says psychiatrist 
jerome kroll of the university of minnesota but things are 
beginning to change not to a great degree but slowly 
kroll and an associate psychiatrist william sheehan recently 
completed a study pointing up the relative disregard of religion by 
mental health specialists compared to patients and people generally 
weve been overlooking an important factor kroll said in a 
telephone interview a lot of our patients believe in god and are 
interested in the church but they arent even asked about it 
its often a source of strength and help to them 
in the american journal of psychiatry kroll and sheehan cite 
surveys finding that 95 percent of the general public profess 
belief in god compared to 55 percent of psychiatrists and 43 
percent of psychologists 
the two also cite a 1986 review that found only 59 or 25 
percent of 2348 psychiatric articles included religion in their 
quantitative data about cases the report adds 
belief in god and in the teachings of the bible the sense of 
an afterlife and social and personal involvement within a church 
community are relevant dimensions of our patients lives that 
certainly deserve more consideration than the psychiatric 
profession has customarily provided 
kroll said that while psychiatrists generally have ignored 
religion as a relevant factor in their patients condition they 
often have automatically blamed it for excessive guilt 
in psychiatry it has long been thought and believed that 
religion brings out unhealthy aspects in people and contributed to 
depression and other mental illness he said our indications 
is that this is not so 
he and sheehan in their study examined religious beliefs 
practices and involvement of 52 psychiatric patients at the 
university of minnesota hospital and clinic 
their rate of belief in major tenets of faith was found to be 
high but patients with major depression and anxiety disorders 
contained the lowest percentage of believers in god the report 
says 
this is contrary to expectations that depressive patients 
feel excessive guilt and blameworthiness and that anger and 
guilt underlies depression the report says 
our depressed patients along with the patients with anxiety 
disorder were the least religiously oriented disagnostic group 
the report says while all those with disorders not associated with 
guilt believed in god 
kroll in the interview noted the sampling was limited but 
added 
often guilt is thought to be religiously inspired this 
indicates that is not so religion has been held to be the culprit 
by some psychiatrists but there is no evidence of it 
were saying its not so 
were saying that the role of guilt in depression is 
overemphasized and is not borne out by the facts the thinking has 
been that anger and guilt underlie depression but when you look 
for the guilt its not there 
kroll 52 is jewish and while sheehan about 30 is roman 
catholic kroll said that psychiatry developed its antagonism to 
religion under the freudian influences of the 1940s and l950s 
traditionally psychiatrists and psychologists have not paid 
much attention to the religious part of life he said they 
hardly ever mentioned it 
but he said attitudes began changing in the 1970s not much on 
the east coast but more so elsewhere as indicated by increasing 
pastoral counsellors in hospitals and the presence of clergy in 
psychiatric wards 
clergy are being used more in psychiatry he said theres 
a coming together of resources in a way that didnt used to be the 
case its increasing 
theres a greater awareness that science just doesnt answer 
all of lifes problems 
he said disagreement still exists in psychiatry about whether 
religion is helpful or hurtful to mental health with both sides 
presenting evidence for their case he added 
most pscyhiatrists tend to take a neutral viewpoint and not 
to pay to much attention to it at all thats why theyve skipped 
over it and havent appreciated how important it was 
</TEXT>
