<TEXT>
production cuts and the first substantial layoffs 
in the auto industry in several years are probable by late summer 
if new incentives offered by us automakers strike out with 
potential car buyers industry analysts said wednesday 
youve got the best team coming into the ninth inning said 
analyst charles brady of oppenheimer amp co of new york weve got 
to get some hits in here if the weather turns bad and you get 
rained out you lose 
brady who has normally been bullish on the domestic auto 
industry and other analysts said ambitious production schedules 
face certain cutting in the second half of the year if sales dont 
recover from an uncharacteristic slump in march 
normally march and april are strong sales months in 
anticipation of that carmakers allowed their inventories to grow 
as they do at the beginning of every year 
but there are differences this year because of recent years of 
healthy sales the market has become increasingly saturated with 
new cars 
automakers and industry watchers expected sales last month to be 
lower than in march 1988 when the industry was beginning the 
secondlargest sales year in history 
cars and trucks assembled by the eight major usbased 
carmakers sold at a rate 116 percent lower in march than they did 
during the same month last year through the first three months of 
1989 sales were off 76 percent 
there is some concern that the auto industry which often serves 
as a leading indicator of the us economys health may be in for 
a rocky time in the early 1990s 
the wall street journal on wednesday quoted sources as saying 
analyst david healy of drexel burnham lambert inc had drastically 
cut his earnings projections for general motors corp ford motor 
co and chrysler corp for 1990 healy declined to discuss the 
report 
if these incentives dont work i think everyone is going to 
mark down their forecasts said donald ratajczak director of the 
economic forecasting center at georgia state university in atlanta 
a lot are riding on these incentives 
each of the big three signaled their concern about sagging sales 
within the last week by offering incentive packages including 
financing as low as zero percent and increased cash rebates on many 
cars and trucks 
if these incentives dont move the sales rate up temporarily 
the companies will have to cut production said healy 
were getting into a better selling season brady said 
weve got excellent rates out there in terms of the incentive 
programs and very good selection 
however he added the third quarter is a question depending 
on how many we sell in april or may last year sales during 
those two months trended just above what proved to be the annual 
rate 
i think they might be able to lift the secondquarter selling 
rate healy said but even then i think youll have a fairly 
skinny third quarter as far as production is concerned 
during march some automakers briefly cut production in what 
they called inventory adjustments longerterm production cuts and 
more layoffs may be on the horizon healy and brady said 
those production cuts probably wont come until the third 
quarter of the year when factories usually shut down to retool for 
the new model year secondquarter production is pretty well locked 
in they said because automakers already have placed orders with 
their suppliers 
youve seen no pullback in the production schedules brady 
said so weve been coming to april with sales mediocre and 
confidence levels among the domestic manufacturers remaining fairly 
high 
the fact of the matter is that production will probably come 
down a little he said weve gotten to the point where we have 
to produce now 
