polaroid corp exposed its first conventional 
film to reporters wednesday billing it as a onesizefitsall 
product that would work for more than 90 percent of the pictures 
snapshooters take 
analysts said the film was fairly ordinary but could do well by 
exploiting consumer confusion over film speeds 
theyve come up with a very clever marketing approach to a 
metoo product said eugene glazer an analyst at dean witter 
reynolds inc 
polaroid said it hopes to get as much as 5 percent of the 
conventional film market which is about 7 billion worldwide at 
retail prices glazer predicted the share would fall slightly short 
of 5 percent but still benefit the instant photography kingpin 
the announcement was widely expected but polaroids stock price 
rose 25 cents a share anyway to 3762 
polaroid under pressure until recently from a 32 billion 
takeover bid by investor roy e disney is hoping to improve its 
financial results the company lost 23 million last year after 
special restructuring charges and expenses of 152 million 
instant photography which polaroid founder edwin h land 
created in the late 1940s has had little or no growth in recent 
years while conventional film sales have grown 5 to 10 percent a 
year 
polaroid is hoping its name recognition and nodecisions 
sales pitch will give it a piece of the business dominated by 
eastman kodak co and fuji photo film co ltd 
polaroid is stressing that onefilm which goes on sale thursday 
relieves consumers of having to choose between different film 
speeds such as 100 200 400 and 1000 
but competitors said onefilm is nothing special they said their 
own films have wide exposure latitudes allowing them to be used 
under many different circumstances and they said quality is bound 
to suffer if a film is used in the wrong situations 
its not unusual to have a wide exposure latitude on a film 
all fujis color negative print films have wide exposure 
latitude said paul hudak general manager of the photographic 
products division of fuji photo film usa inc 
fujis position was backed by steven rosenbaum publisher and 
editorial director of modern photography magazine i dont 
believe there would be any great technological difference in 
exposure latitude said rosenbaum who said he tried samples of 
onefilm about a month ago and liked it 
onefilm is not much of a gamble for polaroid rather than build 
huge new film factories it is buying the film from minnesota 
mining amp manufacturing co or 3m which is making it according to 
polaroid specifications 
name recognition counts for a lot too polaroid has about 11 
percent of the blank videocassette market making it one of the 
market leaders it buys them from other sources keeping profit 
margins slim 
land more visionary than businessman long opposed getting 
polaroid into conventional film wednesday the company said it was 
extending not abandoning the instantfilm business pioneered by 
land 
we are achieving the contemporary vision of polaroid as a 
complete resource for imaging products including instant 
electronic and now conventional media carl j yankowski the 
vice president of marketing said at a news conference 
i macallister booth polaroids chief executive announced the 
intention to sell conventional film last july a few days before roy 
disney nephew of the late walt disney announced his shamrock 
holdings inc was bidding for the company 
polaroid also created an employee stock ownership plan 
repurchased shares and sold shares to a sympathetic third party in 
an effort to fend off shamrock shamrock recently said it was 
selling back its nearly 5 million shares to the company 
