<TEXT>
a massachusetts utility wednesday became 
the second bidder for public service co of new hampshire making 
an offer it says would be worth 235 billion if the seabrook 
nuclear power plant operates commercially 
new england electric system of westboro which already serves 
60000 new hampshire customers through its granite electric co 
offered 14 billion if seabrook never overcomes 
evacuationplanning and financial obstacles to a commercial license 
public service the lead seabrook owner with a 36 percent share 
of the 59 billion project sought protection under the bankruptcy 
laws 14 months ago because of the plants licensing delays 
public service is exploring a sale of its assets as one possible 
reorganization option whatever it decides to do will be subject to 
bankruptcy court approval 
in january connecticutbased northeast utilities new englands 
largest power company announced a bid it said would be worth 2 
billion if seabrook runs and 12 billion if it doesnt 
both proposals would spin off public services 36 percent 
seabrook share into a separate company from which the reorganized 
utility would buy power if the reactor operates 
at a news conference new england electric president john rowe 
said his companys bid would offer greater return for public 
service investors and lower rates for its 360000 customers than 
northeasts offer and public services own reorganization proposal 
rowe called his proposal a kinder gentler acquisition 
kinder to investors and gentler to customers 
like the northeast proposal new england electric would keep 
public service under new hampshire regulation public service has 
proposed seeking federal regulation to bypass a state law that bars 
it from charging ratepayers for seabrook before it operates 
commercially however the company also is negotiating with its 
creditors and the state on a rate plan that could leave the utility 
independent and stateregulated 
rowe would not provide specifics on which creditors would get 
what under his companys offer 
our interest is in making the largest pie for investors with 
the smallest amount of cooking ingredients from the customers 
rowe said how the pie is cut well let the investors decide 
however rowe speculated that public service debenture holders 
and stockholders likely would get most or all of the new seabrook 
company northeast has said unsecured creditors would get the 
seabrook share and stockholders would have to negotiate with them 
for a piece of it 
jim neidhart chairman of the public service unsecured creditors 
committee called the new england electric bid a substantial 
improvement over northeasts offer 
however neidhart said by telephone from new york were 
concerned about any deals that in effect orphans seabrook and 
gives debenture holders a return only if the plant operates 
richard tilton lawyer for public services preferred and common 
stockholders said the new offer has many problems but is a good 
starting point he said it demonstrates that northeasts bid was 
not serious 
while saying he is quite concerned about the seabrook 
spinoff proposal tilton said that nees attitude is more likely 
to lead to a consensual plan than the nu approach of trying to wipe 
out the shareholders 
but bob busch northeasts chief financial officer said in a 
telephone interview that based on a very preliminary analysis we 
feel quite comfortable with our bidding position with respect to 
neess offer 
he would not say whether his companys bid is worth more than 
new england electrics however 
its pretty difficult to determine how much real additional 
value is there versus what just looks good busch said of the new 
bid 
public service president john duffett said the new offer was 
another step toward recognizing proper value for psnh 
but duffett expected more offers would be made and said we 
have an obligation to give those proposals due consideration before 
we decide if the sale of the company is the best option for 
emerging from bankruptcy 
larry smukler senior assistant attorney general and the states 
lead negotiator in rate talks with public service said new england 
electric and northeast are qualified to take over the utility 
both of them are talking about rates that are higher than what 
the state has been talking about but if they make a deal and 
want to negotiate with us well negotiate with them smukler 
said 
