<TEXT>
a consultant who had bribed a navy 
engineer for information on a big pentagon contract hounded 
executives of a defense firm for money once the company was awarded 
the job according to tape recordings played in federal court 
wednesday 
private consultant william parkin also testified in person for 
the prosecution against three former executives of teledyne 
electronics of newbury park calif eugene sullivan george kaub 
and dale schnittjer in the trial in us district court 
he said that he himself accepted about 50000 in bribes in a 
10year period during the 17 years he worked for the navy before 
1983 
parkin the former director of acquisition for the navys joint 
missile project has pleaded guilty to bribing a government 
official and to other charges in the governments investigation of 
pentagon fraud and kickbacks in the 150billionayear purchasing 
system 
he is cooperating with the government in the current trial of 
the three former executives who are accused of bribery conspiracy 
and making false statements 
the government rested its case at the end of the day opening 
the way for the defense to begin calling witnesses on thursday 
parkin has admitted that he indirectly paid stuart berlin a 
navy engineer who also has pleaded guilty for confidential data 
about a 24 million contract that teledyne electronics was awarded 
in july 1987 the contract called for making handheld radar 
equipment 
prosecutors say parkins arrangement with teledyne electronics 
called for him to be paid 10000 in november 1985 and 150000 
once the contract came through 
in the wiretapped telephone conversations parkin who worked 
with private consultant fred lackner who also has pleaded guilty 
in the case complained to the executives that he hadnt been paid 
his 150000 even though the firm got the contract 
in november 1987 parkin told schnittjer that his associates 
were upset they hadnt been paid 
they feel theyve done their job and they are entitled to 
their just reward parkin said 
schnittjer replied i can understandive been delinquent 
in a conversation with sullivan who was schnittjers 
predecessor parkin complained every day i get strung along 
sullivan told parkin i dont think theyre giving you credit 
for this he added as far as i know dale was working to take 
care of this 
again parkin reiterated his situation my guys keep calling 
me they want their money 
the government contends that the three defendants knew about a 
deal that parkin and lackner had to pay berlin for information the 
private consultants were working with michael savaides the former 
washington marketing manager for teledyne according to testimony 
savaides also has pleaded guilty to charges in the case 
teledyne electronics ultimately paid the first installment 
6250 of the 150000 to parkin in march 1988 payments ceased 
shortly afterward when the federal probe known as operation ill 
wind was made public in june 
defense attorneys say their clients were in the dark about the 
illegal activities 
under crossexamination parkin said that over 10 years he 
collected about 50000 in that period in bribes he did not 
elaborate on the nature of the bribes or what he did for them 
in a softspoken voice parkin recounted persuading teledyne 
electronics executives they needed his services to win the 24 
million contract 
parkin acknowledged that the company stood a very good chance 
of winning the contract even without his help he also said it 
wasnt going to be a lot of work that he planned to do on it 
detailing his work as a private consultant parkin said he often 
bluffed in his conversations with people i embellished both 
ways he said 
</TEXT>
